HTTp: Hyper Text Transfer Protocol
-> Communication b/w servers and clients
-> HTTP is stateless (every req is independent similar to transactions)
HTTPS:  Hyper Text Transfer Protocol Secure
->Data is encrypted. encrypted by SSL/TLS certificate

HTTP METHODS:
Get: Retrieves data from server
POST: submit data to server
PUT: Update data already on the server
DELETE: Deletes data from server

HTTP header fields:
i) Req headers: cookies,accept-xxx, content-type,content-length,authorization,user-agent, referrer
ii) Res headers: server, set-cookie,content-type, content-length,date
iii) General headers: Req URL, Req method, Status code, Remote address, Referral policy
In URL: method-path-Protocol

HTTP Status Codes:
1xx: Informational
Request received / processing
2xx: Success
Successfully received, understood and accepted
3xx: Redirect
Further action must be taken / redirect
4xx: Client Error
Request does not have what it needs
5xx: Server Error
Server failed to fulfil an apparent valid request

Examples of status codes:
200 – OK
201 – OK created
301 – Moved to new URL
302 - A 302 status code is a temporary redirect that tells the browser to fetch the requested resource from a different URL
304 – Not modified (Cached version)
400 – Bad request
401 – Unauthorized
404 – Not found
500 – Internal server error

--getpostman.com > where we get all the html code and info about headers, response etc from urls


-----------------------HOW INTERNET WORKS-------------------------
-> Internet is a wire which is buried in the ground
-> Computers that we use are not servers they are actually clients which are connected indirectly to internet through Internet Service Provider(ISP)
-> Anywhere two or more parts of the internet intersect there's a piece of equipment called router. Routers direct your packets around the internet

---------RESTFUL SERVICES ----------------------------------------------
REST: REpresentational State Transfer
Example endpoint to work with customers: http://vidly.com/api/customers   -> In RESTFUL API we term  customers as resources
By sending a req to this endpoint we can do CRUD operations with customers
https://graph.facebook.com/youtube ---- we made an API req to fb's graph APIin which we'll get a JSON response 
https://graph.facebook.com/youtube?fields=id,name,likes ----> we get json response with id,names and likes
Server - maps.googleapis.com, resource - /maps,/api,/geocode,/json
maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=chicago&sensor=false   --- return json as a response
instagram.com/developer > Click on API Console  we can extract lat and long from google apis and then paste in instagram API console, we'll get whatever image or anything available at that particular location
---------------------------------------PHASE1------------------------------------------
FASTAPI:
-> Create a directory using mkdir > Navigate to the created directory > create another directory > navigate to that > create a python virtual env using 'python -m venv .venv' 
> activate the virtual env using '.venv\Scripts\activate' > check for python using 'where python' which gives venv python.exe path
> After venv creation install fastapi
> in main.py file include the below code and run 'fastapi dev' in powershell
from fastapi import FastAPI
app=FastAPI()
@app.get("/")
async def root():
    return {"msg":"Hello"}

OPEN API: FastAPI generates a "schema" with all your API using the OpenAPI standard for defining APIs. This schema definition includes your API paths, the possible parameters they take
In OpenAPI, each of the HTTP methods is called an "operation".

